TY  - JOUR
AU  - Venti, Steven F.
AU  - Wise, David A.
T1  - Have IRAs Increased U. S. Saving?: Evidence from Consumer Expenditure Surveys*
PY  - 1990
Y1  - 1990/08/01
DO  - 10.2307/2937894
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 105
IS  - 3
SP  - 661
EP  - 698
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - The vast majority of Individual Retirement Account contributions represent net new saving, based on evidence from the quarterly Consumer Expenditure Surveys (CES). The results are based on analysis of the relationship between IRA contributions and other financial asset saving. The data show almost no substitution of IRAs for other saving. Estimates are based on a flexible constrained optimization model, with the IRA limit the principal constraint. The implications of this model for saving in the absence of the IRA option match very closely the actual non-IRA financial asset saving behavior prior to 1982. IRA saving does not show up as other financial asset saving in the pre-IRA period.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2937894
ER  - 



