TY  - JOUR
AU  - Caballero, Ricardo J.
T1  - Expenditure on Durable Goods: A Case for Slow Adjustment*
PY  - 1990
Y1  - 1990/08/01
DO  - 10.2307/2937896
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 105
IS  - 3
SP  - 727
EP  - 743
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - For more than a half a decade the fact that expenditure on durables can be well approximated by a random walk has remained a hidden puzzle, challenging almost any theory in which agents smooth the use of their wealth. This paper shows that once a nonparsimonious approach is used, or lower frequencies of the data are examined, the fact itself disappears; changes in expenditures on durables reveal a degree of reversion consistent with the permanent income hypothesis (PIH), although this reversion occurs at a rate significantly slower than what is suggested by a frictionless PIH model.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2937896
ER  - 



